rounds.response:
Current holdings (net value):  
Wheat 16 × 6 = 96  
Wood 16 × 10 = 160  
Sheep 13 × 12 = 156  
Brick 10 × 24 = 240  
Ore 10 × 32 = 320  
TOTAL = 972

Key observation: Ore is my highest-value per-unit good, and Brick is my second-highest.  
Both previous offers (1 Brick ⇄ 1 Ore) were rejected, showing that
- Player 0 values 1 Ore at least 1.0 Brick, and  
- Player 0 values 1 Ore at most ~2.5 Brick + 0.5 Sheep.

Until more information is revealed about Player 0’s ratios, I will try a modestly favorable bundle that:
(1) Removes the lumber-heavy Wheat/Wood I already have in abundance,  
(2) Acquires more high-value Ore and Brick,  
(3) Leaves me with ≥5 of every good so production chains aren’t broken.

With that in mind, I make the following offer to Player 0.

[Offer: 3 Wheat, 3 Wood, 1 Sheep -> 2 Brick, 1 Ore]

rounds.response:
Let’s look at the current value of the resources I would receive vs. what I would give up:

Offer from Player 0  
I give: 1 Ore (value 32)  
I receive: 1 Brick (value 24)  
Net gain = 24 – 32 = –8  
That actually hurts me, so I must refuse unless I can make some other gain from the interaction.

But so far the opponent only offered that exact 1-for-1 swap, nothing else is on the table.  
Therefore my optimal move is to [Deny].

rounds.response:
Round has stalled so I need to change the picture.  
Ore and Brick are my biggest gains; Sheep is mid-value; Wheat and Wood are low-value, plentiful, and expendable.  
I can comfortably offer big bundles of Wheat/Wood plus a little Sheep to tempt Player 0 into off-loading extra Ore or Brick at what looks like “bargain” rates for them but still yields me high-value stuff.

I will package eight of my lowest-value resources (4 Wheat + 4 Wood) plus one mid-value Sheep (all totaling only 88 val-points given up) to ask for two each of high-value Brick and Ore (112 val-points coming in). That’s a straight +24 to me while still leaving me with plenty of each type.

[Offer: 4 Wheat, 4 Wood, 1 Sheep -> 2 Brick, 2 Ore]
